17
00:01:31.660 --> 00:01:34.820
the work that we are doing in the lab, trying to understand how the extracellular

18
00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:38.320
matrix and extracellular matrix-related programs regulate metastatic

19
00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:38.920
dormancy.

20
00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:43.460
As you probably know, metastasis is the primary cause of death of cancer patients,

21
00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:47.380
and it is a very complex process in where cancer cells have to undergo multiple

22
00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:49.960
transitions in order to colonize a distant site.

23
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.520
They have to actively degrade the extracellular matrix in order to invade into the

24
00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:57.460
stroma, intravasate and extravasate from the blood vessels, and eventually

25
00:01:57.520 --> 00:02:01.080
colonize these distant sites in where they're not going to restore

26
00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:04.860
proliferation immediately. They're going to enter in a period of tumor dormancy

27
00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:08.741
that can last for many years before they restore proliferation and start

28
00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:12.860
forming metastatic lesions. So my lab has been focusing on understanding the

29
00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:16.600
biology of these disseminated tumor cells by utilizing different

30
00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:20.540
high-resolution imaging technology in order to understand from a spatiotemporal

31
00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:24.180
point of view, what is the dynamics of the cells during dissemination.

32
00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:28.380
And I would like to share with you some of the aspects that we've been touching

33
00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:32.320
during this cascade. So I would like to start showing you how we actually look at

34
00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:34.740
these disseminated tumor cells in the primary tumor.

35
00:02:35.310 --> 00:02:38.820
This is a process that we can study by doing intravital

36
00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:42.710
microscopy, as you can see in this cartoon, where we can implant the tumors or

37
00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:43.020
have

38
00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:47.840
mouse transgenic models and expose the tumor by doing either a skin flap

39
00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:51.240
surgery and putting directly the mouse under the scope or implanted

40
00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:56.120
windows that allow us to visualize the tumor over

41
00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:59.870
multiple imaging sessions. By combining this with two-photon microscopy,

42
00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:03.829
we're capable of access this tissue and perform imaging with low

43
00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:05.840
photobleaching and low phototoxicity.

44
00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:09.680
That will allow us to really capture the dynamic of the tumor microenvironment in

45
00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:13.400
real time, as you can see in this movie, in where you can see tumor cells

46
00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:17.220
escaping from this primary tumor in blue and blood vessels

47
00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:21.160
around. So by doing this type of imaging, what we learn is that there's

48
00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:23.660
a lot of activity within the primary tumor.

49
00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:27.220
And these disseminated tumor cells are very active.

50
00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:29.460
There are different type of motile behaviors.

51
00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:33.540
You can see in this movie of a breast tumor, MDA231,

52
00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:37.860
and where you can see in the yellow arrow what we call multicellular streams,

53
00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:42.269
and in a white arrow, what we call solitary movement, in where the cells are moving

54
00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.280
as a single unit. So all these type of movements

55
00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:48.200
require active remodeling of the extracellular matrix.

56
00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:51.900
You can see this stream that is moving along this collagen fiber in red,

57
00:03:52.300 --> 00:03:55.800
and eventually, the cells are capable of degrading the matrix and made a way

58
00:03:56.420 --> 00:03:58.620
to intravasate into the blood vessels.

59
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.740
What we learn is that these disseminated tumor cells actually carry

60
00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.980
some dormancy signature that actually help them to remain

61
00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:10.360
dormant at the distant site. And those factors include, for example, TGF-beta,

62
00:04:10.460 --> 00:04:14.340
that contribute to building this dormancy niche when they reach a

63
00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:15.760
distant site, as we will see later.

64
00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:21.260
But in order to eventually colonize efficiently at this site, cells got

65
00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:23.360
to extravasate from the blood vessels.

66
00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:26.800
And again, this is a process that require extensive extracellular matrix

67
00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:29.060
remodeling. And we've been studying this

68
00:04:30.120 --> 00:04:33.740
in collaboration with Ben Marty, David Matthews, by using

69
00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:37.860
zebrafish models. In this system, we can inject the cells in the duct of

70
00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:41.840
Cuvier, and the cells disseminate through the vasculature, and we can do imaging

71
00:04:41.860 --> 00:04:45.580
at the tail of this fish in order to capture this extravasation step.

72
00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:49.480
So we were very fortunate to collaborate with Eric Betzig, Tian Ming,

73
00:04:49.580 --> 00:04:53.440
and Gokul, and utilize one of his latest development, the MoSEC,

74
00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:55.440
which is a lattice light sheet

75
00:04:56.300 --> 00:05:00.020
combined with adaptive optics in order to acquire with high spatiotemporal

76
00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:02.340
resolution this process of tumor cell extravasation.

77
00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:06.360
So I'm going to share with you some of the movies that came out from those studies,

78
00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:09.820
and I will start with this one in where you can see tumor cells.

79
00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:13.860
In this case, we're using MDA231 cells labeled with F-actin in the

80
00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:17.660
blood vessels in orange. So what you can notice is that there is cells

81
00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:21.540
rolling in the vasculature, but you can also notice that there is a cell that

82
00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:23.840
already established the first contact with the endothelium.

83
00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:26.969
And you can see the cell that is actively exploring this

84
00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:31.460
endothelial area, extending this finger-like protrusion that are going to establish

85
00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:33.200
this first contact with the endothelium.

86
00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:37.400
We can see this here in more detail, in where you can see this cell that is

87
00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:40.980
actively protruding in the area that is in contact with the endothelial cells.

88
00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:44.240
You can see all the actin machinery polarizing to that area.

89
00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:47.680
You can see these finger-like protrusions that the tumor cell is forming.

90
00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:51.200
These are called invadopodia. These are structures that are required to

91
00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:54.980
degrade the basement membrane that are localized in that area of contact in order

92
00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:57.700
to start degrading the extracellular matrix.

93
00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:02.620
Eventually, the cell combine all this protrusive activity into a unique

94
00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:06.320
pseudopod, as you can see in the cell in the middle, and this pseudopod is

95
00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:10.670
helping the cell to make their way through the endothelium, and they

96
00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:14.564
are ready to get at the extravascular space.Eventually, the

97
00:06:14.644 --> 00:06:18.404
cells extravasate, and they can survive in these perivascular niches in where

98
00:06:18.444 --> 00:06:22.084
they're going to trigger all these dormancy pathways that keep them in this

99
00:06:22.944 --> 00:06:26.184
quiescent state. So my lab has been really interested in

100
00:06:26.244 --> 00:06:30.024
understanding what are the mechanisms that keep these cells in this quiescent

101
00:06:30.103 --> 00:06:31.124
state, and what trigger

102
00:06:32.504 --> 00:06:34.344
their awakening and their dormancy.

103
00:06:34.924 --> 00:06:38.904
But what we have to take into account is that when we talk the tumor

104
00:06:38.924 --> 00:06:42.884
dissemination and the time to metastasis, we have to take into consideration

105
00:06:42.944 --> 00:06:46.464
that these cells can disseminate very early during tumor progression through a

106
00:06:46.503 --> 00:06:50.384
process that has been described as and early tumor cell dissemination.

107
00:06:50.424 --> 00:06:52.584
So these cells escape the tumor very early.

108
00:06:52.604 --> 00:06:54.244
They can colonize all the sites, and there's

109
00:06:55.304 --> 00:06:59.104
mechanisms that keep the cells in this dormant state are activated.

110
00:06:59.484 --> 00:07:02.744
Now, the patient undergo primary tumor

111
00:07:03.344 --> 00:07:07.044
recession. They're being treated, but the cells still survive at this distant site

112
00:07:07.124 --> 00:07:10.844
evolving, and eventually they are capable of relapse and form metastatic

113
00:07:10.904 --> 00:07:13.424
lesions, as you see by this purple area.

114
00:07:13.484 --> 00:07:17.444
So the field has been really focused on understanding what is the biology behind

115
00:07:17.504 --> 00:07:17.704
these

116
00:07:18.664 --> 00:07:22.464
disseminated tumor cells, how they can remain dormant, what trigger their

117
00:07:22.524 --> 00:07:25.954
awakening in order to define ways in order to eliminate this.

118
00:07:26.434 --> 00:07:29.934
And what we've been learning from the work on many labs in the field, it is what

119
00:07:29.964 --> 00:07:32.684
we summarize here as these dormancy hallmarks.

120
00:07:32.704 --> 00:07:35.724
The best definition we have for these cells is that they are quiescent.

121
00:07:35.984 --> 00:07:39.144
They are arrested in G0. They activate survival pathways.

122
00:07:39.204 --> 00:07:40.544
They also evade the immune system.

123
00:07:41.444 --> 00:07:43.904
They have an intense epigenetic reprogramming

124
00:07:45.144 --> 00:07:49.044
within the genome. The part that we've been focusing in the

125
00:07:49.104 --> 00:07:52.554
recent years is in the context of the extracellular matrix and how

126
00:07:52.564 --> 00:07:56.264
tumor-derived ECM actually contribute to the formation

127
00:07:56.584 --> 00:08:00.524
of these niches and how this can signal back to dormancy.

128
00:08:02.124 --> 00:08:05.844
And as you know, the extracellular matrix is the extracellular component, is the

129
00:08:05.944 --> 00:08:08.264
cellular components of tissues and tumor.

130
00:08:09.164 --> 00:08:12.404
It's produced by fibroblasts within the tumor microenvironment, but also tumor

131
00:08:12.484 --> 00:08:15.404
cells are very active in producing extracellular matrix.

132
00:08:15.424 --> 00:08:19.144
And all of that make up the composition of this ECM

133
00:08:19.204 --> 00:08:20.214
that take into account

134
00:08:21.144 --> 00:08:23.784
the stiffness of the matrix in the three-dimensional organization.

135
00:08:23.804 --> 00:08:24.504
Now,

136
00:08:25.884 --> 00:08:29.464
as important as the matrix is the receptors that the tumor cells express in order

137
00:08:29.484 --> 00:08:33.084
to interpret that matrix as they move along the metastatic cascade are

138
00:08:33.144 --> 00:08:36.965
also really important in order to interpret these different extracellular matrices.

139
00:08:37.544 --> 00:08:41.174
So the question that we've been asking in these recent years was whether these

140
00:08:41.184 --> 00:08:44.454
disseminated tumor cells that I was showing you at the beginning, that they are

141
00:08:44.644 --> 00:08:47.344
escaping the primary tumor. They can control their

142
00:08:48.204 --> 00:08:51.744
fate at the distant site by regulating the composition of the

143
00:08:51.784 --> 00:08:54.804
extracellular matrix and the three-dimensional architecture.

144
00:08:54.933 --> 00:08:58.864
And indeed, what we found is that these disseminated tumor cells that

145
00:08:58.904 --> 00:09:02.824
become dormant, they're very proactive in secreting extracellular matrix, in

146
00:09:02.884 --> 00:09:06.384
particular extracellular matrix that is enriched in collagen.

147
00:09:06.414 --> 00:09:08.674
That's what we call pro-quiescent ECM niche.

148
00:09:09.064 --> 00:09:12.373
And we focus our studies in one of the collagen that it was

149
00:09:12.404 --> 00:09:15.734
highly produced by this dormant cell, which is collagen III.

150
00:09:16.764 --> 00:09:17.184
So this

151
00:09:18.084 --> 00:09:21.924
increase in collagen deposition give rise to this extracellular

152
00:09:22.004 --> 00:09:25.564
matrix that has a specific 3D architecture, as you can see in this

153
00:09:25.664 --> 00:09:29.104
3D reconstruction of this matrix here coming from these dormant cells.

154
00:09:29.144 --> 00:09:32.244
This enrichment in collagen III give this matrix this

155
00:09:33.024 --> 00:09:36.104
more curly and disorganized architecture that is

156
00:09:36.544 --> 00:09:39.844
characteristic of these cells that are becoming dormant.

157
00:09:40.904 --> 00:09:44.334
Now, the question that we wanted to understand is how this matrix that is produced

158
00:09:44.544 --> 00:09:48.404
signals back to the cells to keep them in this quiescent dormant state.

159
00:09:48.924 --> 00:09:52.104
And the way we did that is by taking tumor cells and putting in different

160
00:09:52.144 --> 00:09:55.704
extracellular matrix context. And for this experiment, we use a

161
00:09:55.784 --> 00:09:59.704
biosensor that actually help us to identify the cells that are in G0.

162
00:09:59.744 --> 00:10:03.064
This is a CDK2 biosensor that localize within the

163
00:10:03.104 --> 00:10:04.904
nucleus when the cells are dormant.

164
00:10:04.933 --> 00:10:05.584
And so in this movie,

165
00:10:06.664 --> 00:10:10.153
right here, what you can see, this is one of our dormancy models in the head and

166
00:10:10.264 --> 00:10:13.924
neck tumor. When we put the cells in collagen III, you can see the sensor is

167
00:10:13.984 --> 00:10:17.933
strongly localized in the nucleus, pointing out to the quiescent state of these

168
00:10:17.944 --> 00:10:21.234
dormant cells, and they surrounded the cell of this collagen III matrix that

169
00:10:21.244 --> 00:10:22.174
encapsulate the cells.

170
00:10:23.044 --> 00:10:26.864
Now, if we take a proliferative cells and we put them first in collagen I, you can

171
00:10:26.904 --> 00:10:29.604
see that the cells are actively migrating.

172
00:10:30.304 --> 00:10:34.044
You can see the sensor shuttling between the nucleus and the cytoplasm, suggesting

173
00:10:34.064 --> 00:10:36.464
that the cells are going through the cell cycle.

174
00:10:36.764 --> 00:10:40.444
But if you put now the cells in collagen III, you can start seeing how the matrix

175
00:10:40.484 --> 00:10:42.524
is pushing the cells in this quiescent state.

176
00:10:42.904 --> 00:10:46.344
We see the sensor localized in the nucleus, and we start seeing the rearrangement

177
00:10:46.764 --> 00:10:50.244
of the matrix. So basically, what this shows us is that the matrix can actually

178
00:10:50.304 --> 00:10:54.144
signal to dormancy in order to keep the cells locked in this dormant

179
00:10:54.304 --> 00:10:58.164
state. And how they do that? So we found that indeed the dormant

180
00:10:58.224 --> 00:11:01.504
cells in collagen III can increase the expression of one of the collagen receptors,

181
00:11:02.104 --> 00:11:06.064
DDR1, and through a STAT1, they can trigger the signaling that keep the cells

182
00:11:06.104 --> 00:11:09.844
in this quiescent dormant state. And if we interfere

183
00:11:09.904 --> 00:11:12.784
with this niche, we can actually break this

184
00:11:13.984 --> 00:11:16.304
quiescent, and the cells restore proliferation and form

185
00:11:17.284 --> 00:11:18.044
metastasis.

186
00:11:18.844 --> 00:11:22.704
Now, this process of production of matrix and remodeling of the extracellular

187
00:11:22.744 --> 00:11:25.784
matrix by dormancy is a process that is very active.

188
00:11:25.853 --> 00:11:29.764
You can see in this movie now, this is, again, dormant cells in our head and neck

189
00:11:29.824 --> 00:11:33.124
modeling, where you can see they express an active marker.

190
00:11:33.224 --> 00:11:36.364
They are actively protruding. They are actually

191
00:11:37.024 --> 00:11:40.704
interacting with the matrix, actively remodeling in order to build this niche.

192
00:11:40.804 --> 00:11:43.124
So they are very active in remodeling the matrix.

193
00:11:43.484 --> 00:11:47.124
So we wanted to go a little bit deeper and try to understand how

194
00:11:47.224 --> 00:11:51.114
actually the formation of these matrices is regulated in this

195
00:11:51.144 --> 00:11:51.784
dormant cell.

196
00:11:52.984 --> 00:11:56.964
And as you know, these collagens that the cells produce are triple

197
00:11:56.984 --> 00:11:59.704
helix. They synthesize the single chains,

198
00:12:00.824 --> 00:12:03.404
are synthesized in the endoplasmic reticulum.

199
00:12:03.734 --> 00:12:06.704
And within the endoplasmic reticulum, there is a series of post-translational

200
00:12:06.784 --> 00:12:09.144
modifications that take place in order to form

201
00:12:10.384 --> 00:12:12.924
collagens that are stable at 37. And those

202
00:12:13.804 --> 00:12:16.844
post-translational modifications include proline hydroxylation, lysine

203
00:12:17.424 --> 00:12:21.404
hydroxylation, that form hydrogen bonds between the different chains to make a

204
00:12:21.464 --> 00:12:24.924
structure that is stable and can be secreted and incorporated within the

205
00:12:24.944 --> 00:12:27.820
extracellular matrix.So this process

206
00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:30.660
is taken care of by a series of enzymes,

207
00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:35.600
P4H and LEPRL, that regulate collagen proline hydroxylation, and as

208
00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:38.950
I mentioned, it contributes to the stability of this collagen at

209
00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:43.170
37 degrees. So we ask the question whether these dormant cells,

210
00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:47.410
beyond producing large amounts of matrix, they are very efficient in controlling

211
00:12:47.410 --> 00:12:51.260
the production of matrix by regulating these processes that control

212
00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:55.420
the proline hydroxylation to make a stable collagen ECM.

213
00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:57.820
And what we found was very interesting.

214
00:12:58.060 --> 00:13:01.880
We look at the expression of these collagen hydroxylases in our

215
00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:05.860
dormancy proliferative models, and what we found is that indeed, some of these

216
00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:09.980
proline hydroxylases are upregulated in these dormant cells, in particular

217
00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:13.200
P4HA2, which is one of the proline hydroxylase of collagens.

218
00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:17.400
So we hypothesize that through upregulation of the activity of this enzyme,

219
00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:20.100
these cells are very efficient in forming this matrix that is

220
00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:24.940
very stable and have a high content of proline

221
00:13:24.980 --> 00:13:28.500
hydroxylation. But is it required for dormancy as part of

222
00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:32.380
this ECM regimen program? We knock it down in our

223
00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:35.740
head and neck cancer model, and as you can see, compared with the control, in the

224
00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:39.760
absence of P4HA2, we see the restoration of growth when we put these cells in the

225
00:13:39.800 --> 00:13:42.140
lung, and the cells start forming metastasis.

226
00:13:42.180 --> 00:13:46.160
And we found also similar results in a breast cancer dormancy model,

227
00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:50.120
the D2OR model. Now, how is now the absence

228
00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:53.760
of P4HA2 impacting the landscape of the extracellular

229
00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:57.320
matrix? We start collaborating with Peggy Angel in South

230
00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:00.920
Carolina and perform a special proteomics in order to

231
00:14:00.980 --> 00:14:04.820
understand the special distribution of collagen in these highly

232
00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:07.580
hydroxylated species within these tumors.

233
00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:12.000
And as you can see in this heat map, what we found is, in the absence of P4HA2,

234
00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:15.640
we indeed have a decrease in the abundance of these proline

235
00:14:15.650 --> 00:14:19.460
hydroxylated collagens, collagen III, collagen I, collagen V, that

236
00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:23.060
are actually now decreased within the tumor

